args: I'm not a commander anymore.\nJust a mercenary.
What do you want of me? ...No, I suppose\nthat's a foolish question for a messenger.\nYou bring new orders, I take it?
...Hmph. So they want me to capture the\nprince and drag him home, do they?
Yes. Um...I'm sorry.\nI'm not great at talking.
So long as you convey your message\naccurately, that is all that matters.\nI value that, as does our homeland.
＂Our general back home was delighted\nthat you had not forgotten your mission.＂
You...worked your way into the pocket\nof the prince, just as they wanted.
And the general... Um...the general\nwants you to come back now.
Hmm. I'd figured I'd be left here to rot.
＂If capture is impossible,\neliminate the target instead.＂
Er, yes. And because Alberia is in a\nstate of chaos...such an achievement\nwould... Um...
If I kill the prince now, the unrest in this\nkingdom will only grow—which would\ngreatly please our homeland.
Y-you just tore up your orders!
Go home, little messenger. Go home and\ntell them that I will carry out this mission\nin my own way.
Whether it comes to capturing or killing\nthe prince, I'll be the one to decide.
Glad I was around to hear that.
Ranzal? What are you doing here?
We caught word that someone was\nskulking about outside, so we decided\nto strengthen our patrols.
Ah. I see you have all come, then.
I think we deserve an explanation, Victor.
It seems I can make no excuses.
But it's my fault! They tracked me, and—
With them, it's safer to show no readiness\nto fight.
Please forgive her exuberance.\nShe is rather devoted to her duty.
Start talking, Victor. We'll decide what to\ndo you with you after that.
I am from a country in northern Grastaea.\nI serve as a general in the military, and\nswear fealty to our royal family and crown.
A general, eh? I thought ya fought with\na touch too much strategy for a standard\nmerc.
My land is a poor one, and our winters\nharsh. The struggle for food and\nsustenance is never ending.
And so, after seeing the abundance\nand plenty in Alberia, our rulers\ndecided to mount an invasion.
We sent many spies to this land—\nmyself included.
I was charged with discovering the secrets\nof Alberia's legendary dragon bloodline.
I have heard enough from this man,\nYour Highness! Pray permit me to—
Easy, Elisanne. Let's hear everything\nVictor has to say first.

I believed that the best way to get close to
those in power would be to demonstrate
my strength, and so I took on the guise
of a wandering mercenary.
Eventually, I met a number of young\npeople on various battlefields,\nand we ended up forming a troupe.
I figured being a mercenary captain would\ncapture even more eyes—and make my\nmission that much easier to fulfill.
I thought of our band as nothing more than\na means to an end. I was merely using\nthem to accomplish my mission.
But the day my people were slaughtered\nin the Empire's trap, I knew I had made\na grave miscalculation.
I realized how irreplaceable the\nShadewolves had become to me.
So ya decided to take revenge against the\nEmpire? Or rather, ＂the battle isn't over,＂\nwas it?
Heh. I did say that, didn't I. Though if I'm\nto be honest, I really just didn't want to\nadmit my own responsibility for their fates.
No, Victor. The Empire is responsible.
The Empire may have laid the trap,\nbut my foolishness led them to it.

When Alberia became Dyrenell, I planned
to use that unrest to help me get close to
the royal family. My ambition overtook my
common sense.

Perhaps word of that made it to someone.
Because while we thought of the imperial
army as our allies, they surrounded us on
the field of battle and...
Now, I could care less about my homeland\nor royal orders. If I cannot atone for my\nsins, there is no point to living at all.
That is the whole truth.\nBelieve it or not as you see fit.
All I ask is that you spare Noelle;\nI cannot bear to see another of\nthose in my charge die.
You may banish me or torture me\nor execute me as you see fit—\nonly spare this girl's life.
I don't want your life, Victor.
And why not? I am a spy from a foreign\nland sent here to cause you all manner\nof terrible mischief.
You WERE a spy. Things are different now.\nYou said so yourself, did you not?
Because we've fought with each other.\nI've seen your struggles—and your fire.\nThat's enough for me.
Ever since you joined us, you've been at\nthe vanguard in each and every battle,\nhelping me stay out of harm's way.
If you wanted the secret of dragonblood,\nyou would have been trying to put me in\nMORE combat—not less.
That's how I know you're fighting\nfor something deeper.
Bwa ha ha! There ain't a leader alive what\nknows his folks better'n the boss here.
That's why he believes in 'em so strongly.
You're even more estimable than I thought.
But if you understand me, you also\nunderstand the magnitude of my grudge.
I'm not saying I understand all of it.\nBut I know that what you seek isn't\ndone for the sake of cruelty.
That's why I believe in you, Victor.
(I had no further interest in the secret\nof the dragon bloodline...)
(But now I want to know what this man\nwho bears it might accomplish!)
